04807nam a22006495i 9780520971196DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192019cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209711967 a10.1525/97805209711962doi  a(DE-B1597)534766  a(OCoLC)1048661626  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.43qOCoLC223/eng/202302161 aWard, Meredith C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aStatic in the System :bNoise and the Soundscape of American Cinema Culture /cMeredith C. Ward. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCalifornia Studies in Music, Sound, and Media ;v100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Noise and the Concept of the Cinema Soundscape -- t1. Songs of the Sonic Body: Noise and the Sounds of Early Motion Picture Audiences -- t2. The Film Industry Lays the Golden Egg: Noise, Electro-Acoustics, and the Academy’s Adjustment to Film Sound -- t3. “Machines for Listening”: Cinema Auditoriums as Vehicles for Aural Absorption -- t4. Cinema Theaters as Antiquated as “Edison and His Wax Cylinders”: Mobile Technologies and the Negotiation of Public Noise -- tConclusion: Noises We Will Be Hearing Soon -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this rich study of noise in American film-going culture, Meredith C. Ward shows how aurality can reveal important fissures in American motion picture history, enabling certain types of listening cultures to form across time. Connecting this history of noise in the cinema to a greater sonic culture, Static in the System shows how cinema sound was networked into a broader constellation of factors that affected social power, gender, sexuality, class, the built environment, and industry, and how these factors in turn came to fruition in cinema's soundscape. Focusing on theories of power as they manifest in noise, the history of noise in electro-acoustics with the coming of film sound, architectural acoustics as they were manipulated in cinema theaters, and the role of the urban environment in affecting mobile listening and the avoidance of noise, Ward analyzes the powerful relationship between aural cultural history and cinema's sound theory, proving that noise can become a powerful historiographic tool for the film historian.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMotion picture audienceszUnited States. 0aMotion picture theaterszUnited States. 0aNoise. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2019z9783110605785oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2019 Englishz978311061001708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCA Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065207908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311066763940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520971196?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520971196423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520971196/original  a978-3-11-061001-7  EBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-065207-9  UCA Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  